GETPID(2)                                                                                                   Linux Programmer's Manual                                                                                                   GETPID(2)

NNAAMMEE
       getpid, getppid - get process identification

SSYYNNOOPPSSIISS
       ##iinncclluuddee <<ssyyss//ttyyppeess..hh>>
       ##iinncclluuddee <<uunniissttdd..hh>>

       ppiidd__tt ggeettppiidd((vvooiidd));;
       ppiidd__tt ggeettppppiidd((vvooiidd));;

DDEESSCCRRIIPPTTIIOONN
       ggeettppiidd() returns the process ID of the calling process.  (This is often used by routines that generate unique temporary filenames.)

       ggeettppppiidd() returns the process ID of the parent of the calling process.

EERRRROORRSS
       These functions are always successful.

CCOONNFFOORRMMIINNGG TTOO
       POSIX.1-2001, POSIX.1-2008, 4.3BSD, SVr4.

NNOOTTEESS
       If the caller's parent is in a different PID namespace (see ppiidd__nnaammeessppaacceess(7)), ggeettppppiidd() returns 0.

   CC lliibbrraarryy//kkeerrnneell ddiiffffeerreenncceess
       Since  glibc version 2.3.4, the glibc wrapper function for ggeettppiidd() caches PIDs, so as to avoid additional system calls when a process calls ggeettppiidd() repeatedly.  Normally this caching is invisible, but its correct operation relies on
       support in the wrapper functions for ffoorrkk(2), vvffoorrkk(2), and cclloonnee(2): if an application bypasses the glibc wrappers for these system calls by using ssyyssccaallll(2), then a call to ggeettppiidd() in the child will return the wrong  value  (to  be
       precise: it will return the PID of the parent process).  See also cclloonnee(2) for discussion of a case where ggeettppiidd() may return the wrong value even when invoking cclloonnee(2) via the glibc wrapper function.

SSEEEE AALLSSOO
       cclloonnee(2), ffoorrkk(2), kkiillll(2), eexxeecc(3), mmkksstteemmpp(3), tteemmppnnaamm(3), ttmmppffiillee(3), ttmmppnnaamm(3), ccrreeddeennttiiaallss(7), ppiidd__nnaammeessppaacceess(7)

CCOOLLOOPPHHOONN
       This page is part of release 4.04 of the Linux _m_a_n_-_p_a_g_e_s project.  A description of the project, information about reporting bugs, and the latest version of this page, can be found at http://www.kernel.org/doc/man-pages/.

